         <abstract>
            <p>An analysis is given of the role of rounding errors in the synthetic division algorithm for computing the coefficients of the polynomial g(z) = f(z + s) from the coefficients of the polynomial f. It is shown that if |z + s| â‰… |z| + |s| then the value of the computed polynomial g&lt;sup&gt;*&lt;/sup&gt;(z) differs from g(z) by no more than a bound on the error made in computing f(z + s) with rounding error. It may be concluded that well-conditioned zeros of f lying near s will not be seriously disturbed by the shift.</p>
          </abstract>
